summary: One of my favorite things about Crowley and Aziraphale is that they both picked up different human habits, but they still do...
body:
One of my favorite things about Crowley and Aziraphale is that they both picked up different human habits, but they still do them together.

Aziraphale likes food, so Crowley buys him lunch and sits with him, even though we’ve never actually seen him eat anything.

Crowley likes sleep, and Aziraphale has definitely laid with Crowley, and held him while he slept, even though Aziraphale himself never actually slept.

I like “I don’t understand why you like this, but I will indulge you in it because it makes you happy and I love you” couples.

summary: wacky good omens thought (mostly based on TV canon): its really playing fast and loose with canon sorry[[MORE]] so what if...
body:
wacky good omens thought (mostly based on TV canon):

its really playing fast and loose with canon sorry

so what if crowley is technically the real satan but he’s honestly kind of forgotten after all these years or doesn’t like to think about it but it still counts and so adam is in essence his son (and of course also aziraphale’s)

look okay he’s the snake of eden right? and the more archaic reading of the serpent is that it’s just a normal snake, not a demon. later in christian tradition you got to the idea of the serpent having been satan in disguise. with crowley in good omens being a fallen angel, that’s further from the “normal snake” version but he’s closer to that version by being a minor denizen of the garden, rather than satan himself… right? 

but he’s clearly not a normal snake, he’s got all the supernatural abilities and qualities of a fallen angel. 

adam young has the most extreme reality warping powers of any character besides possibly god herself, supposedly inherited from satan, but he’s able to warp reality to cut himself off from the cumberbatch satan we meet and still after that as a supposed human undo the damage he’s done (and at the end he seems to have minor powers like withering the hedge) so the powers might not really have come from the cumberbatch satan

we’re meant to believe c!satan is a threat in that moment because he can not only intimidate adam but also lash out at everyone there in the scene. punish the rebellious adam for gaining knowledge of good and evil and everyone who encouraged him to do so – you get what I’m saying? satan isn’t satan in that scene, he’s got the same narrative role as the vengeful god of eden. 

so there’s a way to imagine all this where the female voice of god we hear is the real god who has ineffable plans, but the being that schemes up the apocalypse, who continually tests and punishes humanity, the being whose apparent cruelty continually angers and bemuses and disgusts crowley, is the being we see claim to be satan.

and you can imagine crowley rebelling against that god because that’s what he’s continually doing.

so in this interpretation, the angel who rebelled against god is the angel who is the serpent who is later known as crowley. he’s subordinate to hell and to the rules of being a demon because the demons and the angels clearly work together to enforce the status quo and their desire to fight each other is a desire to uphold the system. so basically they’re all servants of the same great plan and the great plan is the satan-god while the ineffable plan is the real god.

and crowley would have had the same power that adam did to reject whatever power he might have had so he can live life the way he wants to. maybe his rebellion was the same as adam young’s – he rejected his original being and chose his form. it was a snake. he wanted to be a snake. he didn’t fall, he sauntered vaguely downwards, following his own desires in life.

but as the actual satan who rebelled that would mean he’s the father of the antichrist. and I’m just saying that adam’s blond hair could have easily come from a certain blond angel that crowley is very fond of hanging around. it could have even happened by accident, without them noticing their essences had combined.

perhaps having an angel and a demon consorting for so long was actually creating the antichrist, as in, crowley and aziraphale’s relationship was this long process of gradual essence mixing that inevitably would lead to a child being born who had all their heavenly and hellish power but would be human incarnate.

we’re meant to believe c!satan is a threat in that moment because he can not only intimidate adam but also lash out at everyone there in the scene. punish the rebellious adam for gaining knowledge of good and evil and everyone who encouraged him to do so – you get what I’m saying? satan isn’t satan in that scene, he’s got the same narrative role as the vengeful god of eden. 

so there’s a way to imagine all this where the female voice of god we hear is the real god who has ineffable plans, but the being that schemes up the apocalypse, who continually tests and punishes humanity, the being whose apparent cruelty continually angers and bemuses and disgusts crowley, is the being we see claim to be satan.

and you can imagine crowley rebelling against that god because that’s what he’s continually doing.

so in this interpretation, the angel who rebelled against god is the angel who is the serpent who is later known as crowley. he’s subordinate to hell and to the rules of being a demon because the demons and the angels clearly work together to enforce the status quo and their desire to fight each other is a desire to uphold the system. so basically they’re all servants of the same great plan and the great plan is the satan-god while the ineffable plan is the real god.

and crowley would have had the same power that adam did to reject whatever power he might have had so he can live life the way he wants to. maybe his rebellion was the same as adam young’s – he rejected his original being and chose his form. it was a snake. he wanted to be a snake. he didn’t fall, he sauntered vaguely downwards, following his own desires in life.

but as the actual satan who rebelled that would mean he’s the father of the antichrist. and I’m just saying that adam’s blond hair could have easily come from a certain blond angel that crowley is very fond of hanging around. it could have even happened by accident, without them noticing their essences had combined.

perhaps having an angel and a demon consorting for so long was actually creating the antichrist, as in, crowley and aziraphale’s relationship was this long process of gradual essence mixing that inevitably would lead to a child being born who had all their heavenly and hellish power but would be human incarnate.

wacky good omens thought (mostly based on TV canon):

its really playing fast and loose with canon sorry
